Sableﬁsh Anoplopoma ﬁmbria inhabit the Paciﬁc Ocean from northern Mexico through the Aleutian Island chain into the eastern Bering Sea. Sableﬁsh are a demersal species that inhabits the continental shelf, the shelf break, and associated gullies at depths up to 2,740 m but more commonly at depths less than 700 m (Mecklenburg et al. 2002). Initially, Sableﬁsh was harvested off the coasts of Washington and British Columbia before the ﬁshery expanded south to Oregon and California and north to Alaska (Hanselman et al. 2014). There are two Sableﬁsh stocks that differ in growth rate, size, and maturity (Green et al. 2014). The Alaskan stock extends from *Corresponding author: mlherrmann@alaska.edu Received May 18, 2015; accepted March 1, 2016

Alaska is the world’s principal supplier of Sableﬁsh Anoplopoma ﬁmbria, a buttery-ﬂavored whiteﬁsh greatly prized in Japan. Sableﬁsh are distributed from Baja California to western Japan, but the majority of commercial catches are from the Gulf of Alaska and the Aleutian Islands off Alaska. The volume and value of landings of this long-lived demersal ﬁsh are comparable to those of the well-known Paciﬁc Halibut Hippoglossus stenolepis. As with Paciﬁc Halibut, Alaska region catches of Sableﬁsh are managed under an individual ﬁshing quota (IFQ) program implemented in 1995. We present a simultaneous-equation market model for Sableﬁsh and use it to examine the linkages between landings volume and exvessel prices and revenues, including the sensitivity of Alaska exvessel prices and revenues to changes in landings, the implementation of IFQs, and changes in the Japanese economy. The model simulations indicate that markets could absorb substantially more Sableﬁsh than can be sustainably harvested from the current stock of Sableﬁsh in the Alaska region. However, sluggishness in the Japanese economy has resulted in overall downward pressure on Alaska region Sableﬁsh exvessel prices. The model simulations indicate that the implementation of IFQs in this ﬁshery signiﬁcantly increased exvessel revenues as a consequence of the longer seasons that resulted from the end to the “race for the ﬁsh.” In addition, we ﬁnd that implementation has helped buffer the ﬁshery against revenue losses associated with reduced catch limits triggered by the decline of Sableﬁsh biomass in the Alaska region. the tip of the Aleutian Islands to northern British Columbia and is centered in the Gulf of Alaska (Figure 1). The southern stock inhabits the waters of British Columbia, Washington, Oregon, and California.

Sableﬁsh were ﬁrst caught in the early 1900s incidental to catches of Paciﬁc Halibut Hippoglossus stenolepis. The stock was lightly exploited until Japanese longline vessels began to exploit the stock in the 1960s (Green et al. 2014). Japanese vessels dominated the commercial harvest of Sableﬁsh through- out the 1960s and into the 1970s. In 1972, a record world harvest of 61,700 metric tons occurred (FAO 2012). With the FIGURE 1. Range of the Alaska Sableﬁsh stock (ADFG 2015). passage of the 1976 Magnuson–Stevens Fishery Conservation and Management Act (MSFCMA), U.S. ﬁshing vessels rapidly displaced the Japanese ﬂeet from this ﬁshery, and the Alaska region Sableﬁsh ﬁshery was closed to foreign ﬁshing in 1985 (Figure 2). Today, the majority of Sableﬁsh are harvested from the continental Paciﬁc Coast of the United States, British Columbia, and Alaska (Figure 3) using longline and pot gear with smaller vessels, most ranging from 30 to 59 ft (9.1–18 m). Sableﬁsh are also caught incidentally in groundﬁsh trawl ﬁsheries. However, the majority of the harvests follow the historic method of setting longlines and pot gear. Since the MSFCMAwas ﬁrst enacted, there have been several major management changes in the Alaska Sableﬁsh ﬁshery. The ﬁrst was the uprooting of foreign vessels—principally Japanese longliners—by 1985. By the time this occurred, the ﬁshery had already began to suffer from overcapitalization, a race for the ﬁsh, compressed seasons, reactive management strategies, and overﬁshing. The Alaska Sableﬁsh harvest peaked in 1988 at ALASKA SABLEFISH FISHERY AFTER IFQ IMPLEMENTATION

37,300 metric tons (the total U.S. harvest that year was 48,800 metric tons). The North Paciﬁc Fisheries Management Council (NPFMC) and the Alaska Department of Fish and Game (ADFG) worked together to slow the inﬂux of capital into the ﬁshery through the development of vessel moratoria and limited entry programs. In 1995, the federal Alaska region Sableﬁsh ﬁshery came under an individual ﬁshing quota (IFQ) program that also applied to the Alaska Paciﬁc Halibut ﬁshery. The effects of IFQ program implementation on ﬂeet structure and seasonal landings were dramatic. Fleet size declined from 1,109 vessels in 1994 to 615 vessels in 1995 (Brinson and Thunberg 2013). In 2013, only 320 vessels participated in the ﬁshery (Fissel et al. 2014). The IFQ program also led to the season length being extended from an average of 14 d in 1994 to 245 d in 2014 (in some management areas it had been as low as 9 d: Sigler and Lunsford 2001). Alaska remains the world’s largest supplier of Sableﬁsh and consistently accounts for two-thirds of world production (Fissel et al. 2014). Japan is the dominant consumer FIGURE 2. Landings of Sableﬁsh by major producers in thousands of metric tons (1950–2013). market for Sableﬁsh, although there are other minor export markets and a relatively small U.S. domestic market. The dom- inance of the Japanese market has been documented in past studies, which have identiﬁed the state of the Japanese economy and prices of competing goods in Japan, as well as the dollar–yen exchange rates, as important drivers of the U.S. exvessel price for Sableﬁsh (Jacobson 1982; Squires et al. 1988; Hastie 1989; Huppert and Best 2004).

The Alaska region Sableﬁsh and Paciﬁc Halibut ﬁsheries have similarities beyond the fact that both are managed under similarly structured IFQ programs. They generate similar levels of exvessel revenue from similar landed quantities, are FIGURE 3. Percentages of world landings of Sableﬁsh in Alaska, British Columbia, and the Paciﬁc Coast of the continental United States (1988–2014). mostly harvested with similar longline gear, and are harvested at overlapping depths (150–1,500 m for Sableﬁsh, 30–300 m for Paciﬁc Halibut). Fishers who hold Paciﬁc Halibut IFQ typically own at least enough Sableﬁsh IFQ to allow them to retain any Sableﬁsh they catch while ﬁshing for Paciﬁc Halibut and vice versa. Unlike Alaska region ﬁsheries for Paciﬁc Halibut, which include several competing user groups (sport, commercial, and subsistence), the Sableﬁsh ﬁshery is overwhelmingly commercial. Another difference is with end markets; whereas Paciﬁc Halibut is primarily consumed in the United States and Canada, Sableﬁsh is mostly exported out- side of North America (primarily to Japan) and can be assumed to have substantially different factors affecting prices. While there has been substantial research evaluating the effects of IFQ program implementation on markets for Paciﬁc Halibut (Herrmann 1996, 2000; Herrmann and Criddle 2006), there has been little analysis of the economic impacts of IFQ implementation in the Alaska region Sableﬁsh ﬁshery. The objective of this study was to quantify the economic consequences of changes in the Sableﬁsh supply due to management actions intended to assure sustainable stocks and economic viability. This objective was achieved by deriving an econometric model that links harvest, price, and revenues in domestic and international markets. Model simulations were used to examine the effects to exvessel price and revenue of changes in Sableﬁsh production, IFQ program implementation, and changes in exchange rates and Japanese income levels.

In developing our model, we relied on several past studies of the ﬁshery for insight into price formation and market structure. We also examined past economic studies of similar ﬁsheries, such as Paciﬁc Halibut. Alaska region Paciﬁc Halibut ﬁsheries have been the subject of numerous studies, in part because of the popularity of Paciﬁc Halibut in the United States and in part due to the value of the ﬁshery. These studies have examined the harvest, processing, and market sectors of the Paciﬁc Halibut ﬁshery and its performance under IFQ management. In comparison, the available economic literature on the Alaska region Sableﬁsh ﬁshery is limited and outdated. To examine the effects of the foreign vessel reduction and increased consumer demand for Sableﬁsh, Jacobson (1982) used annual data from 1971 through 1980 to estimate a single- equation model of the Tokyo wholesale Sableﬁsh price as a function of the quantity of Sableﬁsh traded in the Tokyo whole- sale market, nominal Japanese gross national product (GNP), and the real price of Chum Salmon Oncorhynchus keta. Chum Salmon was chosen as a substitute because, like Sableﬁsh, it was used by consumers in ﬁsh stews. Jacobson (1982) predicted that increased production of Chum Salmon by hatcheries in Japan and the Paciﬁc Northwest would have a negative impact on export prices for Sableﬁsh. However, there is no evidence this has happened, probably due to changes in how that Japanese consumers use Sableﬁsh. At the time of that research, the United States was working toward elimination of foreign ﬁshing vessels from U.S. waters, while anticipating their absence would be ﬁlled by domestic vessels. Due to the long- term changes that followed Americanization of the ﬁsheries, Jacobsen’s (1982) model is not representative of current conditions in the Sableﬁsh market.

Using monthly data from 1981 to 1986, they modeled price transmissions between the Tokyo central whole- sale market and the Alaska and Paciﬁc Coast (California, Oregon, and Washington) exvessel prices. They found that the Tokyo wholesale Sableﬁsh market and the Alaska region ﬁxed- gear exvessel markets were well integrated. Squires et al. (1988) also found that Alaska region Sableﬁsh exvessel prices were sensitive to the volatility of the yen–dollar exchange rate. This was not the case for U.S. Paciﬁc Northwest prices, which reﬂected a strong reliance on local domestic sales. Hastie (1989) expanded on Jacobson’s (1982) model by substituting real GNP for nominal GNP and using quarterly data from 1972 to 1987. In Hastie’s (1989) model, the quantity sold in the Japanese wholesale markets became signiﬁcant, and the responsiveness of price to changes in quantity was estimated to have increased between the 1972–1980 and the 1980–1987 time periods. In addition, Hastie (1989) also reported the results of an export market model based on monthly U.S. export data from 1981 to 1987. Export price was modeled as a function of the Tokyo wholesale price, exchange rates, and inﬂation, and separate models were esti- mated for Alaska and West Coast exvessel prices as functions lagged exvessel prices, Tokyo wholesale prices, and of exchange rates. Hastie (1989) concluded that the Japanese market largely sets Alaska region Sableﬁsh exvessel prices and, in contrast to Squires et al. (1988), that this inﬂuence extends to West Coast exvessel prices.

Huppert and Best (2004) constructed two models of the interaction between Sableﬁsh market prices in Japan and the total supply of Sableﬁsh to examine whether Sableﬁsh farming might be proﬁtable in British Columbia. Huppert and Best (2004) assumed that total exports to Japan could be represented as a direct function of the total allowable catch (TAC) in North America (i.e., exports only varied with quota). Their ﬁrst model regressed Tokyo Sableﬁsh wholesale prices on Sableﬁsh imports, income, and the price of Sockeye Salmon O. nerka. In the second model, Tokyo Sableﬁsh wholesale prices were regressed on Sableﬁsh imports, exchange rates, and the Japanese gross domestic product (GDP). used to estimate price sensitivity to increased levels of supply. Model results indicated that Sableﬁsh exvessel prices in all three ﬁsheries (Alaska, British Columbia, and the U.S. Paciﬁc Northwest) were sensitive to exported quantities to Japan. British Columbia exvessel prices were the most sensitive followed closely by those of Alaska, and Paciﬁc Northwest prices were a distant third. Huppert and Best (2004) concluded that Sableﬁsh farming could be proﬁtable up to a level of 27,000 to 48,000 metric tons per year and that it would depress exves- sel prices for wild harvests. In the 10 years since that study was completed, Sableﬁsh farming has not emerged as a major supply source and appears unlikely to become inﬂuential in the near future. In this study, we developed an econometric model of Sableﬁsh markets based on data that included the 20 years since IFQ management was implemented and data for the 7 years immediately preceding IFQ implementation. A similar modeling approach has been successfully used to examine the inﬂuence of IFQ implementation on exvessel prices and rev- enues in the Alaska and British Columbia Paciﬁc Halibut ﬁsheries. Herrmann (1996, 2000) developed market models of Paciﬁc Halibut ﬁsheries in British Columbia and Alaska, which are both managed under IFQ programs (British Columbia in 1991 and Alaska in 1995). Model results showed that the elongated seasons that followed IFQ implementation substantially improved the commercial revenues. Herrmann and Criddle (2006) further examined the effects of IFQs in the Alaska region Paciﬁc Halibut ﬁsheries and found that the revenue-generated beneﬁts of the program nearly all ﬂowed to harvesters rather than processors. This outcome was also found by Matulich and Clark (2003) who used a different modeling approach.

The market model.—The model was constructed to focus on Alaska region Sableﬁsh exvessel price formation. Since 1985, the United States and British Columbia have accounted for virtually the entire world supply of Sableﬁsh. Since the 1980s, Alaska has been the dominant supply source, with 63% of the balance was provided by ﬁsheries in British landings; Columbia and (13%), Oregon (10%), California Washington (6%) (see Figure 3). While Sableﬁsh are harvested with ﬁxed gear (longlines and pots) and trawl gear, most are harvested with ﬁxed gear, which provides higher product quality; over 92% of the 2014 landings were from vessels operating ﬁxed gear. The majority of the U.S. catch of Sableﬁsh is exported to Japan (85% of all U.S. exports since 1988). Based on trade data, trade publications, and past academic studies it is apparent that the Japanese consumer market is the principal driver of North American exvessel prices. Japan has consistently paid a price premium for imported Sableﬁsh and presumably this reﬂects that country’s preference for more valuable, large, high-quality ﬁsh from Alaska and British Columbia. Smaller Sableﬁsh from Washington, Oregon, and California ﬁll demand in the other smaller markets (including the domestic U.S. market). The U.S. Sableﬁsh export price to all other countries from 1988 to 2013 averaged 36% less than the average export price to Japan.

Given these characteristics of the world Sableﬁsh market—a market with one dominant supplier (Alaska) and one dominate consumer market (Japan)—our market model treated Sableﬁsh price formation as being determined largely by the Japanese market and Alaska landings. The model is represented by three behavioral equations and one market clearing identity, a system of four endogenous variables and four equations. The behavioral equations are: (1) the Japanese import demand for Sableﬁsh from the United States; (2) the allocation of Alaska region Sableﬁsh harvests to Japan; and (3) the exvessel derived demand for Alaska region Sableﬁsh. Sableﬁsh has changed from being primarily consumed in winter stews (for its rich oil content) to being consumed as steaks (kirimi) or in other quality dishes. Paciﬁc Cod Gadus macrocephalus and Walleye Pollock G. chalcogrammus are now more popular as bases for winter soups because they are less expensive (Tom Asakawa, National Marine Fisheries Service, personal communication). Using ﬁsh with a high oil content, such as the Chum Salmon or Sockeye Salmon that were included in historical Sableﬁsh market studies (Jacobson 1982; Hastie 1989; Huppert and Best 2004), is not relevant to analyses that extend to the current market. Sableﬁsh is often sold at supermarkets as kirimi for is also marinated, smoked, and sautéed. home grilling. It Sableﬁsh is not popular in sushi or sashimi dishes due to the risk of parasites in the raw ﬁsh (Asakawa, personal commu- nication). The most commonly mentioned Sableﬁsh substitute is Mero Dissostichus eleginoides (also called Patagonian Toothﬁsh or Chilean Seabass) (Sonu 2000; Huppert and Best 2004; Asakawa, personal communication). However, Mero import prices to Japan are only available for recent years. Because there is no general consensus or statistical evidence that Japanese import prices for other ﬁsh species signiﬁcantly affect the Japanese import price of Sableﬁsh, we elected to include the general price index for meat. Using the generic price of meat as a substitute for a particular modeled ﬁsh species has been effective in models of markets for Paciﬁc Halibut (Herrmann 1996, 2000; Herrmann and Criddle 2006). Even without price increases in the primary market, there are price and revenue advantages to ﬁshers from an individual quota program. As noted in Huppert and Best (2004), a distinct effect of an IFQ is to increase ﬁshers’ bargaining power. They noted that “as a more ‘rational’ man- agement of the [Sableﬁsh] ﬁshery has become the norm in Canada and Alaska, the spread between the exvessel price and Tokyo wholesale price has narrowed” (Huppert and Best Þ instead 2004:4). By using average daily landings Lt=slent of season length alone, one can estimate how average daily catch affects the ability of ﬁshers to bargain for higher prices. Their market power is greatest when landings are low and seasons are long. In 1994, the Alaska Sableﬁsh ﬁshery lasted just 14 d; in 1995, the ﬁrst year the ﬁshery was prosecuted under IFQs, the season was 235 d long. Since 1995, the season has averaged 238 d (Figure 4).

The aggregate model was estimated using annual data over the sample period 1988–2014. This time period coincided with both the ﬁrst year that Japanese Sableﬁsh import statistics were available (following the exclusion of foreign ﬁshing vessels from U.S. waters) and the peak in U.S. landings of Sableﬁsh, which have since seen a reduction due to management decisions predicated on biological considerations. The mean-value own-price elasticity shows the import demand for Sableﬁsh to be elastic, indicating that increased Alaskan landings, with corresponding decreases in export prices and increases in Japanese imports, would increase Japanese Sableﬁsh import expenditures to the United States, holding all else equal. This is not surprising since Sableﬁsh is a high-valued ﬁsh whose landings have been on a steady decline since 1988, when landings were over three times their current imports of level. As reported in Huppert and Best (2004), Sableﬁsh are also very sensitive to changes in the Japanese economy as measured by consumption expenditures. This relationship will be further explored later in this paper. The decision to include the real producer price index of meat as a substitute good for Sableﬁsh is supported by the very strong statistical relationship shown in the estimated equation. It is not surprising that the Japanese consumer, in deciding whether to buy Sableﬁsh, will make a decision partly based on the price of alternative meat products. The cross- price elasticity indicates that for this time period a 1% increase in the Japanese price of meat would be associated with a 3.38% increase in the Japanese import quantity of U.S. Sableﬁsh without a corresponding adjustment in import price (in reality, with nearly all Alaska Sableﬁsh being exported to Japan, the price of imported Sableﬁsh would adjust upwards to clear the market). The high sensitivity of Japanese import demand to meat prices was expected because Sableﬁsh con- sumption is relatively minor in comparison with consumption of other meat products sold in Japan. Accordingly, small changes in the price of meat can lead to large changes in meat consumption relative to the total available amount of Sableﬁsh sold on the Japanese market.

Initial estimates of the demand equation included a variable for season length. Individual ﬁshing quotas have been theo- rized and demonstrated to shift the primary demand for a ﬁsh species outward (Herrmann 1996, 2000; Homans and Wilen 1997). For example, for Paciﬁc Halibut, consumer price −0.021 1,048.8 0.401 −0.361 increases followed the implementation of IFQs due, in part, to a slower-paced ﬁshery, which improved ﬁsh quality from better handling and also allowed producers to take advantage of expanding the volume supplied to the higher-price fresh ﬁsh market. However, nearly all U.S. exports of Sableﬁsh, both pre- and post-IFQs, are frozen prior to shipping. Accordingly, IFQs were not found to boost consumer prices by extending the supply of Sableﬁsh to the Japanese fresh ﬁsh market. Any potential price shifts resulting from quality improvements in the post-IFQ Alaska ﬁshery were not statistically identiﬁed in the import model by inclusion of either a season length vari- able or indicator variable that marked the pre- and post-IFQ periods. Perhaps any quality differences, if they existed, were too small to capture with price movement. The U.S. export supply of Sableﬁsh to Japan (equation 2) was modeled as a function of the Alaska Sableﬁsh landings and the real export price (Table 3). This equation also exhib- ited strong statistical properties and, in particular, the P-value on landings was highly signiﬁcant (the two-sided t-value was 16.1) with the real export price signiﬁcant at the 5% level. Seafood exporters indicated that Sableﬁsh inventories remain low in comparison with other species such as salmon, effec- tively tying supply directly to annual landings (T. Besecker, Dana F. Besecker Co., personal communication).

The coefﬁcient on U.S. Sableﬁsh landings indicates that a 1-kg increase in Alaska Sableﬁsh harvest will lead to a 0.88-kg increase in Sableﬁsh exports to Japan, all else being equal. This reﬂects the fact that the vast majority of Alaska landings have been exported to Japan since the complete exclusion (by 1985) of the Japanese Sableﬁsh ﬂeet from U.S., Canadian, and Russian Federation Sableﬁsh ﬁsheries (Sonu 2000). Finally, the estimated model provides statisti- cal evidence that there is modest responsiveness of export quantities to changes in the Japanese import price. The export price elasticity indicated that as the Japanese import price (in U.S. dollars) increases (or decreases) by 1%, the exports allocated to Japan will increase (or decrease) by 0.30%. This demonstrates that exports are not highly sensi- tive to changes in the export price, but nevertheless there are limited alternative markets (exports to other countries and a domestic market) that provide some pressure to the Japanese export price. Total Revenues and Optimal Static Harvest Levels Alaska region Sableﬁsh harvests have declined from a peak of just over 37,000 metric tons in 1988 to just over 11,000 metric tons in 2014. The steady downward trend in biomass and TAC has placed substantial downward pressure on overall ﬁshery revenues. The ability to set Sableﬁsh TACs to achieve optimal yield has been hindered by the lack of an economic model that captures the relationships between harvest levels, prices, and revenues before and after ITQ implementation. The market model presented here can be used for planning purposes by ﬁshery managers and industry to better under- stand how changes in the TAC for Sableﬁsh will impact ﬁshery revenues. The Alaska and British Columbia Sableﬁsh ﬁsheries entered a period of fundamental change beginning in 1991 when the Canadian Department of Fisheries and Oceans (DFO) implemen- ted an individual vessel quota (IVQ) program for their commer- cial Sableﬁsh and Paciﬁc Halibut ﬁsheries. In that same year, NPFMC approved transition to an IFQ program for both Sableﬁsh and Paciﬁc Halibut ﬁsheries in the Alaska region, a management paradigm shift that took effect in 1995. The intro- duction of the IFQs in these Alaska region ﬁsheries greatly increased the length of the ﬁshing seasons. The 1994 Alaska’s Sableﬁsh ﬁshery was open for 14 d, whereas in 2014 it was open for 245 d. It is estimated that these changes reduced variable costs from 8% to 5% of landed value and also decreased the harvest of immature ﬁsh (Sigler and Lunsford 2001). To estimate the effect of the Alaska IFQ program on Sableﬁsh exvessel prices and revenues, a simulation was run in which the actual season length was replaced with the 1994 season length of 14 d (as if the Alaska IFQ program had not been put into place). The new simulated exvessel price, with the shorter season length, was then compared with the base model (Table 6). Introducing this shortened season length, representative of the pre-IFQ race-for-ﬁsh conditions, resulted in predicted Alaska Sableﬁsh exvessel prices being reduced to $5.79/kg from the actual 2014 price of $7.91/kg. The simula- tion model results indicated that the IFQ program resulted in a Alaska landings (thousand metric tons) TABLE 6. It should be noted that if IFQs had not been put into place in 1995, the season length may have continued to decline, and therefore this projection of the exvessel price increase due to IFQ implementation is a conservative estimate. The exvessel price and revenue forecasts (from 1988 to 2014) under IFQ management and under conventional (race for the ﬁsh) management are shown in Figures 7 and 8. In Figure 7, the price effects of IFQ management are evident, as real exvessel prices under the program consistently exceed those that would have occurred under conventional manage- ment. The change in ﬁshery real exvessel revenues under the two management programs even more pronounced (Figure 8). It is estimated that without the IFQ program, due to the steady decrease in landings between 1988 and 2014, real exvessel revenues would have declined by 6% during this period. However, with the IFQ program, real exvessel revenue has increased by nearly 30% over this period, indicating that the IFQ program has been beneﬁcial to exvessel revenue. Japanese wholesale buyers continue to pay a premium for the larger, higher-oil-content Sableﬁsh caught off the coasts of Alaska and British Columbia. Two primary macroeconomic factors that affect Japan’s consumption and buyer’s behavior are exchange rates and income levels. The market model was simulated to examine the inﬂuence of dollar–yen exchange rates on Alaska region Sableﬁsh exvessel prices. Based on economic theory and the results of past studies, we anticipate that a strengthening yen will increase Japanese demand for Sableﬁsh from Alaska, which will lead to higher exvessel prices paid to Alaska region ﬁshers. The historical relationship between exchange rates and exvessel prices is shown in Figure 9. During the modeled time period, exchange rates were highly variable, with the yen, in general, strengthen- ing against the U.S. dollar (however, in the past few years, the yen has decreased in value while the dollar has strengthened substantially, which bodes poorly for exporters and straining exvessel prices). For example, the extremely high 2011 Sableﬁsh exvessel price coincided with the strongest yen during the modeled period and has been cited as the principal contri- buting factor to the price spike (Welch 2011). Even with recent declines, the 2014 yen had appreciated 19% against the U.S. dollar since 1988. The simulated effect of the 2014 exchange rate, all else held constant, is shown in Table 7. The Sableﬁsh commercial ﬁshery is one of the most lucra- tive ﬁsheries in Alaska and one that is closely linked to the Japanese market. Despite its importance as a ﬁshery and as a case study of management paradigm shift, there have been few analyses of the market for Sableﬁsh or of the impacts of IFQ implementation in this ﬁshery. This study combined what we have learned from previous analyses with information on current ﬁshery and market conditions to update and improve upon past economic analyses and to gauge the economic impacts of the Alaska region Sableﬁsh IFQ program. Through model estimation and simulations that incorporate simultaneous changes in supply and demand, we were able to isolate changes in landings, management regimes, exchange rates, and the Japanese economy as they affect Alaska Sableﬁsh prices and revenues. Based on model results we can conclude that (1) decreased landings have decreased short-run revenues over what they could have been if the TACs had been higher, (2) reduced harvests have raised prices but not nearly enough to completely offset the loss of land- ings, (3) landings could triple from current levels before prices would decrease enough that additional landings would cause revenues to decrease, (4) the Alaska region Sableﬁsh IFQ program led to substantial increases in Alaska exvessel prices and revenues over what they would have been under a con- tinuation of the race-for-the-ﬁsh revenue gains to ﬁshers that mirror what has been found in the Alaska region Paciﬁc Halibut ﬁshery (Herrmann and Criddle 2006), and (5) model

Alaska region Sableﬁsh landings in recent years are similar to the low levels experienced during the mid-1980s. During that period, high Japanese ﬁshing effort led to overexploitation of Sableﬁsh stocks. “Since 1988, relative abundance has decreased substantially” (Hanselman et al. 2014:594). Low biomass and associated landings have contributed to a Sableﬁsh market that can accommodate higher harvests. While these conditions have long been thought to be conducive to the expansion of Sableﬁsh aquaculture, reliance on a market dominated by a single product may have kept exvessel prices too low for aquaculture to emerge to wild-caught Sableﬁsh. The persistent as a market threat decline in Sableﬁsh biomass, combined with a weak Japanese economy, has had long-term impacts to ﬁshery revenues and exvessel prices. The key to the sustained ﬁnancial health of the Alaska region Sableﬁsh ﬁshery may be determined to a large extent by the ability of sound management to rebuild stock biomass and for processors to further develop nascent domestic and non-Japanese export markets.
